<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-290-375  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 290 375.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Byte  Feb 1989 v14 n2 p102(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>A FORTRAN for the Mac forces. (Software Review) (evaluation)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Barker, D.; Loeb, Larry.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Language Systems' FORTRAN compiler succeeds in making the body ofFORTRAN code usable on the Mac, although programmers should notassume it will automatically add Mac features.andP;  The compiler runsunder Macintosh Programmers' Workshop (MPW) Unix-like shell,either Language Systems' version or the Apple version that comeswith the compiler.andP;  FORTRAN produces and links object code, makingit possible for the programmer to use previously created anddebugged programming.andP;  The compiler supports ANSI 77 syntax withextensions designed for the Mac.andP;  For example, ANSI 77 allows sixcharacters in a name and 72 characters per source code line; theMac extension permits 31 characters and 255 characters,respectively.andP;  The traditional FORTRAN assumption of a standardI-O stream is annoying.andP;  Programmers must do some extra work toinclude mouse movement in programs.andP;  The structures to permitcommunication with Mac formatted records in other languages, suchas Pascal, are easy to implement.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Language Systems Corp. (products).andO;Product:   Language Systems FORTRAN (Compiler).andO;Topic:     EvaluationCompilersFORTRAN.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>